yle=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> From Kaslo (Esso station): Drive\u00a010.2 km (6.3 miles) south on Hwy 31 and turn right. Zero odometer.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong> 0.0<\/strong> Start on the Fletcher Creek FSR, signed &#8220;Kokanee Glacier Provincial Park&#8221;. The old south road access is very rough.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 1.1km Go right for the unmaintained Fletcher Lake Trail (not recommended due to high concentration of grizzly bears). Drive 13.6kms. Left goes to Woodbury.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">14.7km Turn right onto a descending side road and drive down to the log landing and park.\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Trail:<\/strong> Follow the skid road eastward into the trees where the trail begins. A rough, sometimes steep and slippery 1,6km hike brings you to Fletcher Lake. Upper Fletcher Lake is reached by a bushwhack of approximately 1.6 km up the valley to the west. Bears have always been a problem around the lakes especially if all litter is not packed out. Fish remains should definitely be packed out.\u00a0\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>This subalpine lake is a popular fishing spot and offers day hiking opportunities to an even more secluded lake. The trails and roads are not maintained because of bear habitat. It is not recommended to come here. Difficulty: difficult\u00a0 Elevation &hellip; <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/21\/fletcher-lake\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"jetpack_post_w